{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523282"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:54:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:54:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13886"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13886"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.04,0.4,0.05,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6503"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109750"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6503"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13886"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92149"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"355"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12926"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12927"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40679"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109750"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 84-year-old woman is admitted to hospital with a two-day history of left iliac fossa pain. Her medical history includes hypertension, hypercholesterolaemia and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. She takes amlodipine and simvastatin. She does not have any other symptoms of significance, apart from some shortness of breath when walking down to the shops.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears comfortable. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 136/86 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals tenderness in the left iliac fossa without peritonism. Cardiorespiratory examination is unremarkable. A diagnosis of acute diverticulitis is made and treated with antibiotics. A chest X-ray is performed as part of her overall management (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management for the radiological finding?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No further action is required","Bronchoscopy","CT scan chest and abdomen","Contrast study","Chest drain"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe chest X-ray demonstrates a para-oesophageal hernia, which appears as a retrocardiac mass with an air-fluid level (triangle in annotated x-ray below). This is an incidental finding in an elderly patient with no relevant symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo further action\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management as the patient is asymptomatic from the hernia. In elderly patients with significant comorbidities, the risks of surgical intervention outweigh the benefits when there are no symptoms. Regular monitoring during routine healthcare visits is sufficient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E would not be helpful in evaluating a para-oesophageal hernia as this is an examination of the airways, not the oesophagus or stomach. It would be indicated if there was concern about an endobronchial lesion, which is not suggested by the imaging findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan chest and abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary in an asymptomatic patient with a clear diagnosis on chest X-ray. While CT can provide detailed anatomical information about the hernia, this would only be warranted if surgical intervention was being considered due to symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContrast study\u003C/strong\u003E such as a barium swallow would provide functional information about the hernia but is not indicated in an asymptomatic patient. This investigation would be appropriate if the patient reported dysphagia or reflux symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest drain\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as the radiological appearance represents herniated abdominal contents, not a pleural collection or pneumothorax. Insertion of a chest drain could cause serious harm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Asymptomatic para-oesophageal hernias in elderly patients do not require intervention.","Para-oesophageal hernias appear as a retrocardiac mass with an air-fluid level on chest X-ray.","Surgical intervention for para-oesophageal hernias should be reserved for symptomatic patients after careful risk-benefit assessment."],"references":["Kaplan JA, Schecter S, Lin MYC, et al.  Morbidity and Mortality Associated With Elective or Emergency Paraesophageal Hernia Repair. JAMA Surgery 2015","Mazer L, Telem DA. Paraesophageal Hernia Current Management. Adv Surg 2021; 55:109\u201322."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92149"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13886"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21133"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21973"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21133"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cphUUqfi8pDj95PgVekOhKNuaEnu6E.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cphUUqfi8pDj95PgVekOhKNuaEnu6E.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":810,"height":857}},{"type":"media","id":"21973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21973"},"attributes":{"mimeType":